text: Kiamycins B and C, unusual bridged angucyclinones from a marine sediment-derived Streptomyces sp. Lin Guo a,1, Ze-ping Xie a,1, Qin Yang a, Ling-ling Feng a, Lu Zhang a, Yue-zhi Zhang a, Xiao-nian Li b, Gennaro Pescitelli c,⇑ a Key Laboratory of Traditional Chinese Medicine Prescription Effect and Clinical Evaluation of State Administration of Traditional Chinese Medicine, Binzhou Medical University, Yantai 264003, China b Department of Analytical Testing Center, Kunming Institute of Botany, Chinese Academy of Sciences, Kunming 650201, China c Dipartimento di Chimica e Chimica Industriale, Università di Pisa, Via Moruzzi 13, 56124 Pisa, Italy Article history: Received 13 February 2018 Revised 17 April 2018 Accepted 23 April 2018 Available online xxxx Keywords: Marine actinomycetes Angucyclinones Kiamycins Structural elucidation Angucyclines and angucyclinones, benz[a]anthracene deriva- tives isolated exclusively from actinomycetes, have drawn much attention for their chemical scaffolds and biological properties, predominantly anticancer and antibacterial activities.1 Since the ﬁrst member tetrangomycin was discovered in 1965, the angucy- clin/one family has grown steadily and achieved great structure diversity via hydroxy substitution, epoxidation, ring cleavage, amino acid incorporation, and glycosylation, etc.2–8 So far, this family has proved to be the largest group of polycyclic aromatic polyketides. However, only few of them possess bridged structures, among which, gephyromycin is the ﬁrst example being isolated from a Streptomyces griseus strain with glutaminergic activity to neuronal cells. Its unprecedented C-3/12a ether-bridged structure might arise from the intramolecular attack of the 3-OH group on a 6a,12a-epoxy precursor, which necessitates the unusual 3S-con- ﬁguration as only present in gephyromycins.9,10

Their structures and stereochemistries were determined by spectro- scopic analyses, single-crystal X-ray diffraction and electronic circular dichroism (ECD) calculations. benz[a]anthracene ring system, from cultures of the Streptomyces griseus obtained from the marine sediment collected off Kiaochow Bay, China. This novel angucyclinone derivative was found to exhi- bit selective activity against the HL-60 cell line.11 Further investi- gation of S. griseus culture extracts has resulted in the isolation of two new analogues, named kiamycins B (1) and C (2) (Fig. 1). Structurally, compounds 1 and 2 possess a unique C-6/12 ether- bridged structure, which is unprecedented in the angucyclin/one family. Moreover, the biogenetically related analogue 3 was iso- lated from the same strain in parallel, and its absolute stereochem- istry was established by ECD calculations. Kiamycin B (1) was obtained as a colorless solid that gave a [M +Na]+ ion in the HRESIMS at m/z 381.1333, appropriate for a molec- ular formula of C20H22O6, which was substantiated by 1H and 13C NMR data. Interpretation of 1D and 2D NMR data revealed the compound to belong to the angucyclinone group and permitted three spin systems to be identiﬁed (Table 1 and Fig. 2). The ﬁrst spin system, including three aromatic protons (H-9/H-10/H-11), showed diagnostic COSY contacts with typical 1H-1H coupling con- stants, which was extended by HMBC correlations from H-9 (dH 6.93) and H-11 (dH 6.66) to C-7a (dC 126.5), and from H-10 (dH 7.17) to C-8 (dC 158.8) and C-11a (dC 143.1) to complete the D-ring (cid:1) 2018 Published by Elsevier Ltd.

of the angucyclinone skeleton. The second spin system contained a set of methylene protons (H2-5) and an oxygenated methine pro- ton (H-6) coupled to each another. The large 2JH,H = 19.1 Hz mea- sured for H-5 protons is in line with reported values for the germinal coupling of diastereotopic protons in gephyromycin.9 This spin system was extended by HMBC couplings from H2-5 to C-6a (dC 77.95) and C-12b (dC 130.69), and from H-6 to C-4a (dC 155.41) and C-12a (dC 44.66) to construct the B-ring and was fur- ther connected through two oxygenated secondary carbons C-7 (dC 73.56) and C-12 (dC 84.73) with D-ring, based on HMBC corre- lations from H-7 to C-6, C-8, and C-11a, and from H-12 to C-6a, C- 7a, C-11 and C-12b to constitute an anthracene substructure. The HMBC cross-peaks from the methyl singlet 3-Me to C-2, C-3 and C-4, and from H2-2 to C-12b and the keto group C-1 (dC 196.93), and from H2-4 to C-4a allowed all carbon signals of the A-ring to be assigned. Meanwhile, the selective three-bond HMBC correla- tions from H2-5 to C-4 and C-12b and from H-12a to C-1 and C- 4a provided the attachment to the B-ring through the quaternary carbons C-4a and C-12b, leading to the construction of a non-qui- nonoid benz[a]anthracene backbone.

The last spin system was established on the basis of COSY con- tacts between H-7 and 7-OH and permitted the 7-OH to be posi- tioned at C-7, which was veriﬁed by HMBC correlations from 7- OH to C-6a, C-7 and C-7a. The remaining substituents had to be positioned at C-3 (dC 70.45), C-6a (dC 77.95) and C-8 (dC 158.81), due to key HMBC correlations from 3-OH to C-2, C-3 and C-4, and from 6a-OH to C-6, C-6a and C-12a and from 8-OMe to C-8. 3R, 6S, 6aR, 7R, 12R and 12aS, with a Flack parameter of 0.17(7). Because this latter was insufﬁciently accurate,12 the AC was addi- tionally proved by electronic circular dichroism (ECD) as described below. Kiamycin C (2) was obtained as a colorless solid that afforded a [M+Na]+ ion in the HRESIMS at m/z 363.1219, consistent with a molecular formula of C20H20O5, differing from 1 by the loss of a molecule of water. A comparative analysis of 1H and 13C NMR spec- tra between 1 and 2 identiﬁed the same angucyclinone skeleton but showed major differences in the A-ring. With respect to 1, the A-ring in 2 was constituted by a 1,2,3,5-tetrasubstituted ben- zene ring, as revealed by the following HMBC correlations (Fig. 4): 1-OH with C-1 (dC 154.44), C-2 (dC 113.07) and C-12b (dC 121.99); 3-Me with C-2 (dC 113.07), C-3 (dC 135.98), and C-4, (dC 120.46); and H-5/H-6 with C-4a (dC 137.05). This structure was fur- ther conﬁrmed by NOE contacts of 1-OH with H-2, of 3-Me with H- 2/H-4, and of H-4 with H-5. The relative conﬁguration of 2 was identical to that of 1 based on the NOEs of H-6 with 6a-OH, of 6a-OH with H-12a, and of H- 12a with H-7 and H-12 (Fig. 4). Crystals of 2 could not be obtained, however, the absolute stereochemistry of 2 was determined by comparing experimental and calculated electronic circular dichro- ism (ECD).

The AC of compounds 1 and 2 was determined following an established protocol,13,14 based on the comparison of ECD experi- mental and calculated spectra. formers found thereof were optimized with density functional the- ory (DFT) at the xB97X-D/6-311+G(d,p) level in vacuo. Six and ﬁve low energy conformers with relative energies within 3 kcal/mol were obtained for 1 and 2, respectively (see Supporting Informa- tion). ECD calculations were run with time-dependent DFT (TDDFT)15 with various functionals (B3LYP, PBE0, CAM-B3LYP, xB97X-D) and the def2-TZVP basis set in vacuo, and Boltzmann- averaged using internal energies at 300 K. The average spectra cal- culated at CAM-B3LYP/def2-TZVP level on (3R, 6S, 6aR, 7R, 12R, 12aS)-1 and (6S, 6aR, 7R, 12R, 12aS)-2 were in good agreement with the respective experimental spectra (Fig. 5). The above anal- ysis conﬁrmed the AC of 1 found by X-ray, and the AC of 2 to be the same as of 1 for the corresponding chirality centers, which is expected from biogenetic considerations. Although the ECD spec- trum of compound 2 is rather weak, the signal-to-noise ratio is suf- ﬁcient, and the g-value (De/e) for the major peak at 215 nm is 1(cid:1)10(cid:3)3, well above the accepted threshold of 10(cid:3)5 for signiﬁcant ECD spectra. The absolute stereochemistry of compound 3, which was not assigned upon its ﬁrst isolation,3 was established as (3R, 6aR, 7R, 12R, 12aS)-3, using the same computational approach. Because of the lack of the ether bridge, compound 3 is much more ﬂexible than 2, thus as many as 20 distinct low-energy DFT conformers with relative energies within 2.5 kcal/mol needed to be included in the calculations (Supporting Information). Still, the agreement between experimental and B3LYP/def2-TZVP calculated ECD spec- tra (Fig. 6) was good enough to assign the absolute conﬁguration. Because of the remoteness of the chirality center at C-3 form the others, the AC at C-3 cannot be safely assigned by the above approach. However, on the basis of biogenetic considerations, we infer the same 3R conﬁguration for compounds 1 and 3. It is worth mentioning that the optical rotation reported for compound 3 (or its enantiomer) isolated from Streptomyces sp. CB01913 was nega- tive, [a]27 D (cid:3) 4.2 (c 0.07, DMSO),3 while the present value is positive, [a]25 D + 37.2 (c 0.24, MeOH). Because of the different measurement conditions, however, no conclusion may be drawn on the respective AC.

A plausible biogenetic route for compounds 1–3 is proposed (Scheme 1) to originate from acetate as landomycins.16 Acetates undergo a series of oxidation and reduction with the aid of type II PKS enzymes to yield the intermediate UWM6, which can pro- vide the previously co-isolated 8-O-methylrabelomycin and 8-O- methylrabelomycin by oxidation and methylation,17 and continues through stepwise reduction to form the intermediate b and the subsequent nucleophilic attack of the 12-OH group on C-6 to give compound 1,18 followed by the loss of H2O to afford 2. Compounds 1 and 3 were screened for cytotoxic activity against eight human cancer cell lines of non-small-cell lung carcinoma (NCI-H460 and NCI-H1975), hepatocellular carcinoma (JHH-7 and HepG2), lung adenocarcinoma (HCC 827), breast cancer (MDA- MB-231), glioma (C6), and leukemia (HL-60). Compound 3 showed selectively cytotoxic activity towards NCI-H1975 cell lines with an IC50 of 17.8 lg/mL. In contrast, compound 1 showed no activity against all tested cell lines up to 128 lg/mL.

In summary, two new bridged angucyclinones, kiamycins B (1) and C (2), possessing an unprecedented 6,12-epoxybenz[a]an- thracene skeleton, were produced by a marine sediment-derived Streptomyces sp. strain M268 together with a structurally related derivative 3. Furthermore, 8-O-methylrabelomycin and 8-O- methylrabelomycin, previously isolated from the same strain, were hypothesized to be the precursors of compounds 1–3.
